Open letter to USA, Israel and Gulf states, facing Iranian missile attacks

Dated: 1st March 2026

Your Majesties,
On behalf of the people and leadership of the Republic of Balochistan, we extend our deepest sympathies to your nations following the recent, unprovoked missile and drone strikes carried out against your capitals, business hubs, airports, metro systems, hotels, and other civilian public spaces. The Republic of Balochistan and Baloch nation is also concerned about the safety and wellbeing of our Baloch communities living in the gulf. These reckless attacks targeting innocent civilians and vital economic infrastructure represent grave violations of international law and constitute war crimes perpetrated by the radical regime in Tehran.

We unequivocally condemn these acts of terror and aggression, which have endangered the lives, prosperity, and stability of the entire region. We further express profound concern at credible evidence that these attacks have been facilitated, supported, or coordinated by elements within the Pakistani military establishment and its associated deep-state networks. Pakistan’s longstanding anti-Israel and anti-America state posture reflected in ideological indoctrination, diplomatic hostility, and tolerance of extremist mobilization has for decades intersected with Iranian proxy agendas to destabilize the broader Middle East and Indian Ocean regions.

Reports suggests that today ISI-linked religious groups have stormed the United States Consulate in Karachi and a United Nations office in Gilgit-Baltistan underscore the escalating risks posed by this nexus between the radical regimes.

For generations, the Baloch national movement has warned the international community including the Western world, the United States, and the Gulf nations about the expanding web of radical funded proxies, sectarian militias, and transnational terror networks cultivated by the Iranian regime and enabled by its partners. Our warnings were rooted not in conjecture but in lived experience: the Baloch people have endured systematic repression, cross-border militancy, and the militarization of our homeland by both Iran and Pakistan.

For more than a century, successive Iranian regimes have pursued systematic anti-Baloch, anti-Kurd, and anti-Ahwaz policies subjugating, displacing, and silencing thousands of innocent people through political repression, demographic engineering, and militarization. Today, the consequences of those long-standing policies are no longer confined within Iran’s borders. The same machinery of coercion and proxy violence that devastated peripheral nations within Iran has now arrived at the doorstep of the Gulf. The threat you face today is the external projection of a century-old internal doctrine of domination.

We respectfully call upon your esteemed governments to recognize the Baloch people’s right to freedom, and to take the historic step of opening official Balochistan representative missions and embassies in Tel Aviv, Washington, Abu Dhabi, Manama, Kuwait City, Riyadh, Doha and globally. Such diplomatic recognition and presence would not merely symbolize solidarity it would establish a forward platform for coordinated security dialogue, counter-terrorism cooperation, and maritime safety initiatives linking the Gulf with South and Central Asia.

Republic of Balochistan

