Mir Yar Baloch 
2 Mach 2026

The Republic of Balochistan strongly condemns the recent reckless and inflammatory remarks attributed to Reza Pahlavi, son of the late Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. Such statements, which carry undertones of intimidation toward historic and distinct nations, are deeply concerning and counterproductive to any vision of peace, coexistence, or democratic transition in the region.

Historical grievances remain vivid in the collective memory of the Baloch people. During the 1970s, the former Iranian monarchy under Mohammad Reza Pahlavi extended military assistance including aircraft, pilots, and financial support to the government of Zulfikar Ali Bhutto of Pakistan amid operations in Balochistan that resulted in thousands of civilian casualties and widespread suffering. Pakistan and Iran's operation killed three thousand Baloch civilians in a single week. These events are not distant abstractions; they are lived history for thousands of families.

Any renewed rhetoric that threatens the identity or existence of non-Persian nations under Iranian occupation including Baloch, Kurds, Ahwazi Arabs, Azeris, Lurs, and others only deepens mistrust. These communities constitute 50% of the population in Iran and inhabit regions of immense cultural, geographic, and economic importance. Many of these areas include extensive coastlines, critical trade corridors, mineral-rich lands, and strategically significant territories.

The people of these regions are not peripheral actors; they are historic nations with distinct languages, cultures, and identities. Calls implicit or explicit for their marginalization or suppression, whether under a monarchical or clerical framework, undermine the very principles of equality and independence that modern governance demands.

The contrast between political systems whether led by clerical authorities or monarchist figures becomes meaningless if the underlying approach toward non-Persian ethnicities remains rooted in central domination and exclusion. A change in attire or political branding does not equate to a change in policy or mindset. Sustainable stability can only emerge from genuine independence, equal rights, cultural recognition, and the democratic consent of all constituent nations.

The Republic of Balochistan reiterates that the Baloch, Kurds, Ahwazi, Azeris, and other communities possess vast natural and human resources. Their people deserve the right to determine their political future through peaceful and democratic means free from threats, coercion, or imposed authority.

Respect for pluralism, recognition of historic identities, and adherence to international principles of right to liberation are the only viable paths toward lasting peace and regional stability. Any leader who aspires to legitimacy must embrace these principles unequivocally.

